1
00:00:18,525 --> 00:00:20,588
Got to move the camera around.

2
00:00:20,629 --> 00:00:23,391
Good evening all.

3
00:00:23,913 --> 00:00:25,535
I trust you had a fruitful day.

4
00:00:25,554 --> 00:00:29,280
I don't say happy, but I hope it has been happy.

5
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:36,609
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambodasa.

6
00:00:37,469 --> 00:00:45,039
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambodasa.

7
00:00:45,576 --> 00:00:53,289
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa.

8
00:00:53,789 --> 00:00:59,219
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

9
00:00:59,238 --> 00:01:02,645
I've gone and brought a floodlight, but it seems to be casting shadows.

10
00:01:03,426 --> 00:01:06,150
That's a bit of a drag, isn't it?

11
00:01:07,513 --> 00:01:10,858
Oh well, so long as you can see my amazing head.

12
00:01:12,745 --> 00:01:22,543
I hope some of you were able to, I think a lot of you were able to join the Buddha celebrations this evening, which I thought were really fantastic.

13
00:01:22,703 --> 00:01:29,454
So I want to move on to another discourse over the next two or three days.

14
00:01:30,516 --> 00:01:36,507
And then on Monday, I'm starting a course, a Vipassana course with the

15
00:01:37,365 --> 00:01:38,968
with the Gaia group.

16
00:01:39,528 --> 00:01:41,272
So it's Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday.

17
00:01:41,331 --> 00:01:43,596
You're welcome to join it.

18
00:01:44,236 --> 00:01:55,313
I'm just thinking, I'll email the connections later on, I think, or I'll send it out with a news bite.

19
00:01:56,215 --> 00:02:00,841
And I'll be doing the usual thing of, I think I'm meditating at eight o'clock in the morning.

20
00:02:01,649 --> 00:02:02,450
Something like that.

21
00:02:02,629 --> 00:02:17,867
Anyway, I shall send details or better still, if you think you might want to practice, even if it's only one of the sessions during the day, send me an email and I'll send you the details.

22
00:02:17,927 --> 00:02:19,310
Perhaps that's the best way to do it.

23
00:02:19,330 --> 00:02:21,712
Yeah.

24
00:02:21,772 --> 00:02:27,780
And on those days, I'll probably be doing the just going through very quickly the Satipa Tana discourse.

25
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:30,323
So it's just the next three days that we're looking at.

26
00:02:30,691 --> 00:02:34,917
And I've chosen to do a Sutta called Kanki, the Kanki Sutta.

27
00:02:38,002 --> 00:02:46,294
And I want to read the first part, not because it's so much Dharma, but because it gives you some idea of the society that was in.

28
00:02:46,816 --> 00:02:57,491
So it would seem that in the old days, of course, the Kshatriyas, the warrior caste, the aristocracy, were, of course, the rulers, were at the top of the ladder.

29
00:02:57,995 --> 00:03:03,903
This would have been a time when they were conquering, when they were settling into North India.

30
00:03:04,705 --> 00:03:15,600
And of course, going really back, they would have been chieftains and the Brahmins would have been their shamans, their witch doctors, as we used to call them.

31
00:03:15,621 --> 00:03:16,763
They'd be the shamans.

32
00:03:17,231 --> 00:03:24,984
As time progressed, of course, the shamans gathered or began to develop these verses.

33
00:03:25,444 --> 00:03:32,436
A lot of them were just spells or ways of doing certain rituals to get the better of the gods.

34
00:03:33,217 --> 00:03:42,872
And of course, as they began to settle on the Gangetic plain, by the time the Buddha was there, there was no need for this, you know, warrior caste so much.

35
00:03:42,893 --> 00:03:44,235
They were fighting with each other.

36
00:03:44,687 --> 00:03:48,954
And the Brahmins began to establish themselves as the superior caste.

37
00:03:48,973 --> 00:04:03,796
And I think we joined that time that the idea was that they came from the mouth of Brahma, the warriors came from the shoulders of Brahma, the workers and the trades people and all that came from the body of Brahma.

38
00:04:03,817 --> 00:04:07,322
And of course the Sudras, the ones right at the bottom came from the feet.

39
00:04:08,723 --> 00:04:14,171
And it would seem that in the East of India, present day Bengal,

40
00:04:14,506 --> 00:04:19,372
the Brahmins had established themselves as the top caste.

41
00:04:19,773 --> 00:04:22,877
But it hadn't really established itself where the Buddha was.

42
00:04:23,678 --> 00:04:25,942
And so there was a bit of argy-bargy going on.

43
00:04:27,324 --> 00:04:29,968
And I think we catch this in this particular discourse.

44
00:04:31,149 --> 00:04:39,500
So on one occasion, the Blessed One was wandering in the Kosalan country with a large sangha of bhikkhus, and eventually he arrived at the Kosalan Brahmin village.

45
00:04:40,004 --> 00:04:42,427
I think you still get that in India.

46
00:04:42,668 --> 00:04:48,956
I'm almost, well, I'm not absolutely sure, but villages will be Brahmin or Kshatriyas or whatever.

47
00:04:49,357 --> 00:04:50,358
They'll be quite separate.

48
00:04:52,880 --> 00:04:58,309
And he arrives at a village called, the Brahmin village called Upasada.

49
00:04:58,329 --> 00:05:06,079
And there the Blessed One's staying at the God's grove, that's the Deva grove, the Salah tree grove to the north of Upasada.

50
00:05:06,716 --> 00:05:23,598
Now on that occasion, the Brahmin Kanki, who was ruling over Upasada, a crown property abounding in living beings, rich in grasslands, woodlands, waterways and grain, a royal endowment, a sacred grant given to him by King Pasenadi of Kosala.

51
00:05:25,038 --> 00:05:32,168
And then on that occasion, so the householders now decided to go and see the Buddha.

52
00:05:32,822 --> 00:05:38,490
And he had retired, Kanki had retired to the upper story of his palace for the midday rest.

53
00:05:39,132 --> 00:05:45,500
And then he saw the Brahmin householders of Upasada setting forth towards the God's Grove.

54
00:05:45,940 --> 00:05:57,177
When he saw them, he asked his minister, good minister, why are these Brahmin householders of Upasada setting forth from Upasada in groups and bands heading northwards to the God's Grove?

55
00:05:57,949 --> 00:06:13,430
Sir, and then he tells him that the recluse, the Samanap Gautama, that's how he would be referred to, the son of the Sakians who's gone forth from the Sakian clan, has been wandering in the Kosaland country.

56
00:06:15,733 --> 00:06:19,098
So then he sends his minister, he says, tell them to wait.

57
00:06:19,497 --> 00:06:22,882
The Brahmin Kanki will also go to see the recluse Gautama.

58
00:06:24,124 --> 00:06:24,884
And off he goes.

59
00:06:25,372 --> 00:06:31,880
Now, on that occasion, 500 Brahmins from various states were staying in Upasara for some business or other.

60
00:06:32,502 --> 00:06:36,767
And they heard this Brahmin Kanki was going to see the recluse, so they went to see him.

61
00:06:36,788 --> 00:06:40,632
Sir, do not go to see the recluse Gama.

62
00:06:40,673 --> 00:06:45,420
It's not proper for Master Kanki to go and see the recluse Gautama.

63
00:06:45,459 --> 00:06:50,045
Rather, it is proper for the recluse Gautama to come and see you.

64
00:06:50,937 --> 00:07:01,951
For you, sir, are well born on both sides of pure maternal and paternal descent seven generations back, unassailable, impeccable in respect of birth.

65
00:07:02,733 --> 00:07:11,343
Since that is so, Master Kanke, it's not proper for you to go to see Master Gautama, Recluse Gautama, rather Recluse Gautama has come to see you.

66
00:07:11,944 --> 00:07:14,548
You are rich, great wealth, great possessions.

67
00:07:14,882 --> 00:07:18,187
Master of the three Vedas and the vocabularies.

68
00:07:18,307 --> 00:07:21,110
That's the Vedas of the liturgical texts.

69
00:07:21,709 --> 00:07:26,115
Liturgy, phonology, etymology, and the histories as a fifth.

70
00:07:26,636 --> 00:07:28,557
Skilled in philology and grammar.

71
00:07:28,637 --> 00:07:30,098
I did have to look up philology.

72
00:07:30,920 --> 00:07:33,242
It means interpretation of the texts.

73
00:07:34,865 --> 00:07:38,869
And you are fully versed in natural philosophy and the marks of the great man.

74
00:07:39,769 --> 00:07:44,535
You are handsome, comely, graceful, possessing supreme beauty of completion.

75
00:07:44,836 --> 00:07:48,982
with sublime beauty and sublime presence remarkable to behold.

76
00:07:49,884 --> 00:07:54,730
You are virtuous, mature in virtue, possessing mature virtue.

77
00:07:55,211 --> 00:07:57,035
You're a good speaker with good delivery.

78
00:07:57,314 --> 00:08:01,781
You speak words that are courteous, distinct, flawless, and communicate the meaning.

79
00:08:02,199 --> 00:08:08,511
You teach teachers of many and you teach the recitation of the hymns to the 300 Brahmin students.

80
00:08:09,132 --> 00:08:18,788
You, sir, are honoured, respected, revered, venerated and esteemed by the King Pasenadi of Kosala.

81
00:08:19,228 --> 00:08:24,377
You, sir, are honoured, respected, revered and esteemed by the Brahmin Pokharasati.

82
00:08:24,896 --> 00:08:50,652
you sir rule over oppasada a crown property abounding in living beings a sacred grant given to you by the king since this is so master camp is not proper for you to go to the recluse gotama rather it is proper for the recluse gotama to come to you now the brahmin says no now hear me he says right and he says virtually the same about the buddha

83
00:08:51,812 --> 00:08:59,923
Saying that, you know, he came from a homeless nurse to live the life of a recluse, noble in virtue, wholesome, etc., etc.

84
00:09:01,365 --> 00:09:07,533
But then he says, Sirs, the recluse Gautama is free from sensual lust and without personal vanity.

85
00:09:08,515 --> 00:09:17,287
Sirs, the recluse Gautama holds the doctrine of moral efficacy of action, karma, the doctrine of moral efficacy of deeds.

86
00:09:17,807 --> 00:09:20,030
He does not seek any harm

87
00:09:20,264 --> 00:09:22,006
for the line of Brahmins.

88
00:09:23,808 --> 00:09:30,879
The recluse gama has gone forth from an aristocratic family, one of the original noble families.

89
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:35,267
So here we see the caste system in bright colors.

90
00:09:36,749 --> 00:09:44,921
Of course, our class can also be much the same and how they measure themselves as opposed to the other castes.

91
00:09:45,461 --> 00:09:47,384
But in this particular case,

92
00:09:47,668 --> 00:09:51,614
He seems to honor the Buddha with the same sort of accomplishments.

93
00:09:52,735 --> 00:09:57,360
And at the end, there's a repetition of what has become the morning chanting.

94
00:09:58,142 --> 00:10:04,568
Now the Blessed One is accomplished, fully enlightened, perfect in true knowledge and conduct, what he says he does.

95
00:10:05,591 --> 00:10:10,557
Sublime, knower of the worlds, that's the cosmology of Buddhism.

96
00:10:11,336 --> 00:10:17,625
Incomparable leader of persons to be tamed, teacher of gods and humans, enlightened and blessed.

97
00:10:18,820 --> 00:10:20,601
So he goes off.

98
00:10:21,724 --> 00:10:23,085
Now they're all there with them.

99
00:10:26,269 --> 00:10:28,272
So they all go down there.

100
00:10:28,312 --> 00:10:34,980
And then the Brahmin Kanki, together with a large company of Brahmins, went to the Blessed One, exchanged greetings, etc.

101
00:10:36,181 --> 00:10:40,886
And after courteous and amiable talk was finished, he sat down to one side.

102
00:10:42,128 --> 00:10:47,595
Now on that occasion, the Blessed One was seated, finishing some amiable talk with some senior Brahmins.

103
00:10:47,947 --> 00:10:52,552
At the time, sitting in the assembly was a Brahmin student named Karpatika.

104
00:10:53,433 --> 00:11:05,471
Young, head-shaven, 16 years old, he was the master of the three Vedas with their vocabulary, liturgy, phonology and etymology and the histories as a fifth.

105
00:11:05,490 --> 00:11:12,240
Skilled in philology and grammar, he was fully versed in natural philosophy and in the marks of the great man.

106
00:11:13,160 --> 00:11:16,164
While the senior Brahmins were conversing with the Blessed One,

107
00:11:16,634 --> 00:11:19,115
he often broke in and interrupted their talk.

108
00:11:19,297 --> 00:11:30,047
Then the Blessed One rebuked the Brahmin students thus, let not the Venerable Bharavadja break in and interrupt the talk of the very senior Brahmins while they are conversing.

109
00:11:30,687 --> 00:11:34,431
Let the Venerable One wait until the talk is finished.

110
00:11:35,511 --> 00:11:42,678
And when this was said, the Brahmin Kanki said to the Blessed One, let not Master Gautama rebuke the Brahmin student.

111
00:11:43,860 --> 00:11:45,020
The Brahmin student

112
00:11:45,423 --> 00:11:47,105
Kapatika is a clansman.

113
00:11:47,385 --> 00:11:48,287
He is very learned.

114
00:11:48,706 --> 00:11:50,089
He is very good delivery.

115
00:11:50,229 --> 00:11:50,909
He is wise.

116
00:11:50,950 --> 00:11:56,337
He is capable of taking part in the discussion with Master Gautama.

117
00:11:56,717 --> 00:12:05,190
Then the Blessed One thought to himself, surely since the Brahmins honour him, thus the Brahmin student must be accomplished in the scriptures of the three Vedas.

118
00:12:05,850 --> 00:12:11,498
Then the Brahmin student thought, when the recluse Gautama catches my eye, I shall ask him a question.

119
00:12:13,081 --> 00:12:19,591
Then knowing with his mind the thought of the Brahmin student, the Blessed One turned his eye towards him.

120
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:25,539
And the Brahmin student thought, the recluse Gautama turned towards me, suppose I ask him a question.

121
00:12:26,280 --> 00:12:41,062
Then he said to the Blessed One, Master Gautama, in regard to the ancient Brahminic hymns that have come down through oral transmission and in the scriptural collections, the Brahmins come to a definite conclusion.

122
00:12:41,363 --> 00:12:42,585
Only this is true.

123
00:12:43,085 --> 00:12:44,506
Anything else is wrong.

124
00:12:45,649 --> 00:12:47,410
What does Master Gautama say about this?

125
00:12:49,774 --> 00:12:58,886
Now then, Brahmaji, among the Brahmins, is there even a single Brahmin now who says, I know this, I see this by my own personal experience?

126
00:12:58,907 --> 00:12:59,888
I'm paraphrasing there.

127
00:13:00,789 --> 00:13:03,013
Only this is true and anything else is wrong?

128
00:13:03,854 --> 00:13:04,754
No, Master Gautama.

129
00:13:05,815 --> 00:13:19,520
Well, then Brahmins, the ancient Brahmin seers, the creators of the hymns, the composers of the hymns, whose ancient hymns have been formally chanted, uttered and compiled by Brahmins nowadays, that the Brahmins nowadays still chant and repeat.

130
00:13:20,057 --> 00:13:27,304
repeating what was spoken and recited, and then there's a whole load of names of the ancient rishis, the ancient teachers.

131
00:13:27,846 --> 00:13:39,136
Did even these ancient, did even these Brahmin seers say thus, we know this, we see this for ourselves, only this is true, anything else is wrong, everything else is wrong.

132
00:13:39,577 --> 00:13:40,578
No, Master Gautama.

133
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:46,605
So, Bharadwaja, it seems that among the Brahmins, there is not even a single Brahmin

134
00:13:47,176 --> 00:13:52,048
Who can say, I know this, I see this for myself.

135
00:13:52,067 --> 00:13:56,799
And among the Brahmins, there's not even a single teacher or a single teacher's teacher.

136
00:13:56,879 --> 00:14:04,357
Going back to the seventh generation of teachers who say, I know this, I see this by my own personal experience.

137
00:14:04,979 --> 00:14:08,323
The ancient Brahmin seers, the creators of the hymns and so on.

138
00:14:08,924 --> 00:14:18,258
Even these cannot say, we know this, we see this by our own personal experience and that only this is true and everything else is wrong.

139
00:14:19,539 --> 00:14:24,927
Supposing there's a file of blind men, each in touch with the next.

140
00:14:25,886 --> 00:14:30,230
The first one does not see, the middle one does not see, and the last one does not see.

141
00:14:30,652 --> 00:14:36,297
So, Bharadwaja, in regard to their statement, the Brahmins seem to be like a file of blind men.

142
00:14:37,077 --> 00:14:41,182
The first one does not see, the middle one does not see, and the last one does not see.

143
00:14:41,682 --> 00:14:43,062
What do you think, Bharadwaja?

144
00:14:43,423 --> 00:14:48,048
That being so, does not the faith of Brahmins turn out to be groundless?

145
00:14:49,970 --> 00:14:51,291
The Brahmins honour that.

146
00:14:51,831 --> 00:14:55,134
The Brahmins honour this not only out of faith, Master Gautama,

147
00:14:55,503 --> 00:14:57,826
but also out of oral tradition.

148
00:14:58,447 --> 00:15:04,455
Ah, Bharadwaja, first you took your stand on faith, now you speak of the oral tradition.

149
00:15:05,176 --> 00:15:10,263
There are five ways, Bharadwaja, that may turn out in two different ways here and now.

150
00:15:10,803 --> 00:15:11,784
What are these five?

151
00:15:12,426 --> 00:15:15,309
Now, this goes back to the Kalama discourse, right?

152
00:15:15,870 --> 00:15:24,581
How we can use various ways of knowing things in order to prove, inverted commas, what we think is true.

153
00:15:25,236 --> 00:15:28,023
Faith, oral, faith approval.

154
00:15:28,442 --> 00:15:30,027
So that's more to do with the heart.

155
00:15:30,167 --> 00:15:33,693
You have a sort of a heart connection with the teacher, with the tradition.

156
00:15:33,995 --> 00:15:37,761
This is often true of people who are brought up in religious traditions.

157
00:15:38,283 --> 00:15:39,445
They don't question anything.

158
00:15:39,505 --> 00:15:41,710
It's just part and parcel of the way they see the world.

159
00:15:43,174 --> 00:15:44,556
Oral tradition, right?

160
00:15:44,615 --> 00:15:46,258
Just because it's come from the past.

161
00:15:46,278 --> 00:15:49,900
So this is the traditionalists or the fundamentalists.

162
00:15:49,921 --> 00:15:54,664
Reasoned cogitation and reflective acceptance of view.

163
00:15:55,225 --> 00:16:02,331
Now the problem with reason and reflecting, you're always, all this reasoning and reflecting is based on a premise.

164
00:16:03,033 --> 00:16:06,155
If the premise is false, the whole thing comes crashing down.

165
00:16:09,538 --> 00:16:12,961
So these five things may turn out in two different ways.

166
